<% if signed_in? %>
  <table class="front" summary="For signed-in users">
    <tr>
      <td class="main">
        <h1 class="micropost">What's up?</h1>
        <%= render 'shared/micropost_form' %>
        <%= render 'shared/feed' %>
      </td>
      <td class="sidebar round">
        <%= render 'shared/user_info' %>
        <%= render 'shared/stats' %>
        <%= image_tag('feed.png') %>
        <%= link_to "Subscribe", private_user_feed_path(
          @user.username, @user.encrypted_password, :format => :rss) %>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
<% else %>
  <%= link_to "Sign up now!", signup_path, :class => "signup_button round" %>

  <h1><i>Welcome!</i></h1>

  <p>
    Hi and welcome to The Microblog Project. This is basically a website built
    upon the resulting application from following Michael Hartl's tutorial at
    <a href="http://railstutorial.org/book">http://railstutorial.org/book</a>.
  </p>

  <h1><i>What's been added?</i></h1>

  <p>
    On chapter 12 of the said tutorial, Mike listed <a href="http://railstutorial.org/chapters/following-users#sec:extensions_to_the_sample_application">possible extensions</a>
    to the application, which a follower can work on. He said, "implementing one
    or more of these application extensions will help you make the transition
    from following a tutorial to writing original applications of your own."
  </p>

  <p>
    Here's what's been added so far. I'm currently working on the last two extensions.
  </p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <td>1. Replies</td>
      <td>3. Follower notifications</td>
      <td>5. Signup confirmation</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>2. Messaging</td>
      <td>4. Password reminders</td>
      <td>6. RSS feed</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h1><i>Show me the codes!</i></h1>

  <p>
    If you came here to see how far this application has gone from the original
    version, I've listed instructions on the <a href="/help">help page</a> to help you in your
    endeavor. If you're here besides that, why not <%= link_to "sign up", signup_path %>?
  </p>
  
<% end %>
